TY  - JOUR
T1  - Subcontracting, Coordination, Flexibility, and Production Smoothing in Aggregate Planning
AU  - Kamien, Morton I.
AU  - Li, Lode
Y1  - 1990/11/01
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/11/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.36.11.1352
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.36.11.1352
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1352
EP  - 1363
VL  - 36
IS  - 11
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We propose a model in which subcontracting can be explicitly considered as a production planning strategy. Possible market and nonmarket subcontracting mechanisms and their costs are discussed. We show that a class of feasible subcontracting mechanisms in which firms coordinate their production via subcontracts Pareto-dominate other mechanisms. We then offer an example with quadratic cost functions and coordination subcontracts; linear decision rules for production, inventory, and subcontracting are derived. In the example, subcontracting reduces the variability in production and inventory. The same interpretation can be used for flexibility of manufacturing resources.
AB  - We propose a model in which subcontracting can be explicitly considered as a production planning strategy. Possible market and nonmarket subcontracting mechanisms and their costs are discussed. We show that a class of feasible subcontracting mechanisms in which firms coordinate their production via subcontracts Pareto-dominate other mechanisms. We then offer an example with quadratic cost functions and coordination subcontracts; linear decision rules for production, inventory, and subcontracting are derived. In the example, subcontracting reduces the variability in production and inventory. The same interpretation can be used for flexibility of manufacturing resources.
