TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Unified View of the IPA, SF, and LR Gradient Estimation Techniques
AU  - L'Ecuyer, Pierre
Y1  - 1990/11/01
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/11/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.36.11.1364
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.36.11.1364
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1364
EP  - 1383
VL  - 36
IS  - 11
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We study the links between the likelihood-ratio (LR) gradient-estimation technique (sometimes called the score-function (SF) method), and infinitesimal perturbation analysis (IPA). We show how IPA can be viewed as a (degenerate) special case of the LR and SF techniques by selecting an appropriate representation of the underlying sample space for a given simulation experiment. We also show how different definitions of the sample space yield different variants of the LR method, some of them mixing IPA with more straightforward LR. We illustrate this by many examples. We also give sufficient conditions under which the gradient estimators are unbiased.
AB  - We study the links between the likelihood-ratio (LR) gradient-estimation technique (sometimes called the score-function (SF) method), and infinitesimal perturbation analysis (IPA). We show how IPA can be viewed as a (degenerate) special case of the LR and SF techniques by selecting an appropriate representation of the underlying sample space for a given simulation experiment. We also show how different definitions of the sample space yield different variants of the LR method, some of them mixing IPA with more straightforward LR. We illustrate this by many examples. We also give sufficient conditions under which the gradient estimators are unbiased.
